<AbstractNarration>0348392  de los Reyes  Microbial flocs are complex microbial communities that are of fundamental importance to a wide variety of natural processes and engineered applications. The ecophysiology of microorganisms in  floc microenvironments ultimately determines which organisms are present, active, and dominant under  specific conditions.  The research described in this proposal will apply a multidisciplinary approach to characterize the factors that control community structure and function in nitrogen-transforming flocs. The specific objectives of the project are: (1) To determine the effect of microscopic floc structure (size and  shape) on rates and diversity of microbial activities and to establish the diversity, the relative numbers and  spatial arrangement of microorganisms involved in nitrogen removal within flocs; (2) To determine the  impact of bioreactor macro conditions (DO, substrate type and loading) on floc size, shape, and function;  (3) To characterize the carbon- and nitrogen-based metabolic interactions among ammonia-oxidizing, nitrite-oxidizing, and denitrifying bacteria within a floc; and (4) To develop a macroscale model of  nitrogen and carbon removal in activated sludge that incorporates microscale processes in flocs. &lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
